  "doc_id": "33312",
  "text": "Across these cases, trust is not a social value embedded in technological form so much as it is necessary element of technological practice, realized in social relations and communities. Efforts to secure computer systems and networks often focus on implementing more secure \"trustworthy\" technological forms. While we do support these efforts, we approach them with the caution that they provide surety, or confidence, rather than trust [CITATION_1] , reposing all authority in technology, often implemented through strong assurance structures of centralized control. Such systems are potentially brittle, susceptible to global technological failure, and political capture of centralized controls. In contrast, a system which privileges social trust relationships is prone to local failures, but more resilient as a whole, though it requires substantial investment in distributed communities and practices for reliable operation.",
